<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06256269 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06256269 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  SPORT; STATISTIC; GAME; OPINION  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  HOW cutthroat is the competition in your rotisserie or fantasy league?;   Arethere conspiracies among owners to manipulate the trade and waiver rules? Isthere one owner who always tries to take advantage of technicalities? Are youdisgusted at the behavior of your so-called buddies?  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  LEAGUES BREED FRIENDS, FOES  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Rotisserie Report  </MEMO><TEXT>     If so, perhaps it will reassure you to know that not all leagues are likethat.;   Mike Zazula, a San Jose resident, is enthralled by fantasy hockey, arelatively rare obsession that can be difficult to satisfy. But hisdetermination in pursuing the hobby has paid unexpected dividends, including afriendship that started with long-distance trade talk.;   Zazula joined aleague by paying a fee to one of the many fantasy-sports services that set uprules and coordinate competition among people who either can't find a localleague or prefer to test themselves against owners scattered around thecountry.;   In a lot of these leagues, a good discount phone plan isparticularly important, and Zazula used his for frequent conversation with DonBrenner, an owner who lives in Pennsylvania. They met for the first time whenZazula had a business-trip stopover at Philadelphia's airport, and now Zazulastays at Brenner's home when he's in that part of the country.;   Got anunusual story about a friendship that was formed -- or even better, thatunraveled -- because of fantasy-league competition? Give me a call, and pleaseleave a number I can call back if you get my recording.; CONVENTION PUSH:Fantasy Baseball magazine is trying to rally support for the idea of aNational Fantasy Baseball Convention, which would be staged every March andinclude a dealers room for stat services and game companies.;   Anyoneinterested in getting involved with the magazine's lobbying effort shouldwrite to the editor, Greg Ambrosius, at Krause Publications Inc., 700 E. StateSt., Iola, Wis. 54990.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mike Antonucci column  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910912  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  September  </MONTH><PG.COL>  2G  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  312  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday, September 12, 199100256269,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>